>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 105 This character may vary ontogenetically, possibly owing to continued ossification around the dorsal area of the pars cochlearis at a later stage in life.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{14 55 Although the skull is fractured, the outline of the basal part of the skull and the preserved portions of the supraoccipital and frontals suggest that the zygomatic processes likley contacted or at least approximated the postorbital process of the frontal. This is further corroborated by a possible facet for contact with the postorbital process on the tip of the zygomatic process, as well as comparisons with morphologically similar taxa (e.g. Herpetocetus bramblei, Piscobalaena nana).>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 12 Though virtually lost in adults owing to the forwards projection of the supraoccipital, the ascending process of the maxilla is distinctly developed in juveniles, based on which the shape of the process was coded. >
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 105 This character may vary ontogenetically, possibly owing to continued ossification around the dorsal area of the pars cochlearis at a later stage in life.>
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 153 see also Buchholtz (2011:fig.3f-g)>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 12 Though virtually lost in adults owing to the forwards projection of the supraoccipital, the ascending process of the maxilla is distinctly developed in juveniles, based on which the shape of the process was coded. >
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 12 Though virtually lost in adults owing to the forwards projection of the supraoccipital, the ascending process of the maxilla is distinctly developed in juveniles, based on which the shape of the process was coded. >
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 105 This character may vary ontogenetically, possibly owing to continued ossification around the dorsal area of the pars cochlearis at a later stage in life.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 12 Though virtually lost in adults owing to the forwards projection of the supraoccipital, the ascending process of the maxilla is distinctly developed in juveniles, based on which the shape of the process was coded. >
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 12 Though virtually lost in adults owing to the forwards projection of the supraoccipital, the ascending process of the maxilla is distinctly developed in juveniles, based on which the shape of the process was coded. >
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 105 This character may vary ontogenetically, possibly owing to continued ossification around the dorsal area of the pars cochlearis at a later stage in life.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 105 This character may vary ontogenetically, possibly owing to continued ossification around the dorsal area of the pars cochlearis at a later stage in life.>

This is further corroborated by a possible facet for contact with the postorbital process on the tip of the zygomatic process, as well as comparisons with morphologically similar taxa (e.g. Herpetocetus bramblei, Piscobalaena nana).>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 12 Though virtually lost in adults owing to the forwards projection of the supraoccipital, the ascending process of the maxilla is distinctly developed in juveniles, based on which the shape of the process was coded. >
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 105 This character may vary ontogenetically, possibly owing to continued ossification around the dorsal area of the pars cochlearis at a later stage in life.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 12 Though virtually lost in adults owing to the forwards projection of the supraoccipital, the ascending process of the maxilla is distinctly developed in juveniles, based on which the shape of the process was coded. >
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 105 This character may vary ontogenetically, possibly owing to continued ossification around the dorsal area of the pars cochlearis at a later stage in life.>

This is further corroborated by a possible facet for contact with the postorbital process on the tip of the zygomatic process, as well as comparisons with morphologically similar taxa (e.g. Herpetocetus bramblei, Piscobalaena nana).>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 105 This character may vary ontogenetically, possibly owing to continued ossification around the dorsal area of the pars cochlearis at a later stage in life.>

>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 12 Though virtually lost in adults owing to the forwards projection of the supraoccipital, the ascending process of the maxilla is distinctly developed in juveniles, based on which the shape of the process was coded. >
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 27 Note that, in life position, the rostrum would be elevated, and the orbit therefore located below the level of the edge of the rostrum. However, this arrangement differs from the condition seen in balaenids both by virtue of the different kind of rostral curvature (upwards and horizontal and opposed to a full arc) and in terms of the lesser degree of downwards defelection of the supraorbital process in Caperea. In addition, scoring the skull in life position would also deviate from the standard practice used throughout the matrix to orient the skull by resting it on its ventralmost anterior (i.e. the tip of the snout) and posterior (i.e. the postglenoid processes) points. Caperea was therfore here scored as having the orbits located roughly in line with the level of the edge of the rostrum.>
>skipping unsupported (or wrong) TNT command  <{7 105 This character may vary ontogenetically, possibly owing to continued ossification around the dorsal area of the pars cochlearis at a later stage in life.>
